                    <section class="card-body text-center">
                        <p><strong>What: </strong>Whiskey is a grain spirit that is distilled in a continous and/or pot stills and is aged in barresl from some period of time. It can be made from any number of grain and distilled in a number of different ways.</p>
                        <p><strong>Where: </strong><strong>Scotch:</strong>Made in Soctland from inexpensive grains or from malted barley.<strong>Irish: </strong>Only four distilleries reamain running in Ireland, Jameson, Old Bushmills, Kilbeggan and Colley Distillery.<strong>Bourbon and Tennesee: </strong>These Whiskeys require the producer use only brand new charred oak barres fro aging. Both use corn as the primary grain in the mashbill.<strong>Rye: </strong>Made from Rye.<strong>Canadian: </strong>Made in Canada, generaly a blend form a base Whiskey (most often 100% corn) and flavoring Whiskey.</p>
